{"author":{"id":"bef3218ab9e622c28d4147d7158926f9e5cdd171bac03d50d28252af4bc1d303"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1466169372,"nonce":"6/Vxee2WsNZPmzuU/lWzjaC26r0=","metadata":{"github-id":"MDU6SXNzdWUxNjA4ODU1NzA=","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/821","origin":"github"},"title":"R_LIB overwritten by multiple R module packages","message":"I have a(nother!) problem with the trinity package dependencies.\n\nFor example, in the [run_DE_analysis wrapper](https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/blob/master/tools/trinity/run_DE_analysis.xml), there's (among others) a dependency on [DESeq2](https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/blob/master/packages/package_deseq2_1_10_0/tool_dependencies.xml) and then [Limma](https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/blob/master/packages/package_r_limma_3_28_2/tool_dependencies.xml)\nBoth of these modules have a dependency on [R 3.1.2](https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/blob/master/packages/package_r_3_1_2/tool_dependencies.xml).\n\nThe problem concerns the R_LIB variable:\n- it gets set once [by the deseq2 R dep](https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/blob/master/packages/package_r_3_1_2/tool_dependencies.xml#L75)\n- then the deseq2 lib path is [prepended to R_LIB](https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/blob/master/packages/package_deseq2_1_10_0/tool_dependencies.xml#L12)\n- it gets **reset** [by the limma R dep](https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/blob/master/packages/package_r_3_1_2/tool_dependencies.xml#L75)\n- then the limma lib path is [prepended to R_LIB](https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/blob/master/packages/package_deseq2_1_10_0/tool_dependencies.xml#L12)\n\nAt the end, the path to the deseq2 lib is no longer in R_LIB and the trinity script fails because can't find the module.\n\nDo you see a way to solve this? I have thought about replacing 'set_to' by 'prepend_to' in [R package](https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/blob/master/packages/package_r_3_1_2/tool_dependencies.xml#L75) but I suspect it could have some unexpected side-effects.\n\nAnthony (who loves conda :) )","files":null}]}